        ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:44:"MLK Day to be remembered by Fenwick faithful";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:87:"http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/2016/01/mlk-day-to-be-remembered-by-fenwick-faithful/";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:8:"comments";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:96:"http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/2016/01/mlk-day-to-be-remembered-by-fenwick-faithful/#comments";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:7:"pubDate";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:31:"Mon, 18 Jan 2016 21:24:09 -0600";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:41:"http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/?p=1546";s:7:"attribs";a:1:{s:0:"";a:1:{s:11:"isPermaLink";s:5:"false";}}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:9229:"One of the most rewarding aspects of moving back to Chicago after 15 years away is having the opportunity to watch some of the best high school basketball in the country, most notably the Simeon Wolverines.

So when 2015-16 high school basketball schedule was announced, the buzz must have started at Fenwick High School, where students, administrators and alumni saw that their beloved Friars would be hosting the State’s most prominent team, the Simeon Wolverines on the afternoon of Martin Luther King Jr. Day, January 18, 2016.

With temperatures below zero, more than a thousand basketball fans, from young kids to older alumni, poured into the Fenwick gym with late arrivals turned away, the capacity reached.

This was a big game. The two most prominent high school basketball reporters, Michael O’Brien of the Sun-Times and Mike Helfgot of the Tribune, were seated courtside.  WCIU-TV’s play-by-play man Jim Blaney and commentator, Kenny McReynolds, were center court to call all the action live. [caption id="attachment_1552" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/CAVzT25WsAAqCXv.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/CAVzT25WsAAqCXv-300x225.jpg" alt="Jim Blaney (L) and Kenny McReynolds (R) " width="300" height="225" class="size-medium wp-image-1552" /></a> Jim Blaney (L) and Kenny McReynolds (R) [/caption]So even with live television and below zero temperatures, the Fenwick faithful showed up to support their team with the hope of knocking off the high profile team that recently won four State Championships under head coach Robert Smith and delivered Nick Anderson, Derrick Rose and Jabari Parker to the NBA.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/Derrick_Rose_41.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/Derrick_Rose_41.jpg" alt="Derrick_Rose_4(1)" width="240" height="229" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1553" /></a>
This was a big deal, a big game.  The Friars are no pushover. They are the fourth ranked team in the State and beat Bogan earlier in the year in double-overtime at the Proviso West Holiday Tournament. Simeon is ranked third with only two losses, one to the State’s top-seed Morgan Park and the other to Curie at the Pontiac Holiday Tournament.  The Friars also only had two losses, to Morgan Park in the championship at the Proviso West Holiday Tournament followed by a loss to rival Benet Academy.  The team established credibility knocking off two Public League powerhouses in Whitney Young and Bogan. 
[caption id="attachment_1554" align="alignright" width="150"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/6916846.jpeg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/6916846.jpeg" alt="Fenwick coach Rick Malnati" width="150" height="250" class="size-full wp-image-1554" /></a> Fenwick coach Rick Malnati[/caption]

Having watched the Friars play at the Proviso West, I was well aware that they were stacked with talent, led by senior point guard Mike Smith, junior Jacob Keller and sophomore A.J. Nixon. But they also are very well coached by Rich Malnati and his staff and every single Friar player that walks on the court knows the offense, defense and brings an energy and commitment to each play. There were no intimidated Friars to be seen. They were ready to play from the jump ball and with every seat in the gym taken along with all of the standing room viewing areas, electricity filled the gym and expectations were high for a great game. Simeon and Fenwick did not disappoint. 

Mike Smith started the scoring quickly and it seemed with every drive or outside shot, he could not be stopped. With each basket, the Friars faithful cheered loudly, a surround-sound of support for each great play.  Simeon’s senior star Zack Norvell led the attack for the Wolverines with help from lightning-quick point guard Evan Gilyard. Norvell is a knock-down outside shooter, but also a tremendous athlete who will take his talents to Gonzaga next year.  In the first half, each time the Friars pulled away, Norvell and his teammates would close the gap.
[caption id="attachment_1549" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/ct-photos-boys-hoops-fenwick-vs-simeon-2016011-005.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/ct-photos-boys-hoops-fenwick-vs-simeon-2016011-005-300x300.jpg" alt="Friars Mike Smith goes up for layup with Simeon&#039;s Zack Norvell in pursuit. (Photo by Brian Cassella/Tribune)" width="300" height="300" class="size-medium wp-image-1549" /></a> Friars Mike Smith goes up for layup with Simeon's Zack Norvell in pursuit. (Photo by Brian Cassella/Tribune)[/caption]
 
Fenwick’s head coach, Malnati, unleashed the 1-3-1 defense against Simeon in the second quarter, a tactic he used against Bogan quite successfully. This defense takes the opposing team out of attack mode as they are forced to quickly move the ball from side to side with good crisp passes or they turn the ball over. At the half with the score close, smiles filled the faces of the Friar faithful, especially the very energetic student section, as they realized their team could win this game. Everyone looked happy, excited at the thought of winning, as they watched their talented cheerleaders do backflips across the gym and dance team take the floor for a very polished and well-performed presentation. 
[caption id="attachment_1550" align="alignright" width="168"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/ct-photos-boys-hoops-fenwick-vs-simeon-2016011-007.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/ct-photos-boys-hoops-fenwick-vs-simeon-2016011-007-168x300.jpg" alt="A.J. Nixon shows great athleticism on drive to hoop. (Photo by Brian Cassella/Tribune)" width="168" height="300" class="size-medium wp-image-1550" /></a> A.J. Nixon shows great athleticism on drive to hoop. (Photo by Brian Cassella/Tribune)[/caption]
When the second half started, Malnati went to a 2-3 zone defense and it worked fairly well as his team took the lead, going up by 10 at one point.  The Friar's Smith was once again unstoppable and the Wolverines Norvell picked up his pace and energy as he realized they could lose the game, if he didn’t take it over. Both Norvell and Gilyard would score on drives and outside shots as their teammates, especially Josh Thomas, picked up their intensity to force turnovers in the fourth quarter that turned the momentum in favor of Simeon, as a stunned look crossed the collective faces of the Friar faithful. 
[caption id="attachment_1551" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/ct-photos-boys-hoops-fenwick-vs-simeon-2016011-011.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/ct-photos-boys-hoops-fenwick-vs-simeon-2016011-011-300x300.jpg" alt="Evan Gilyard beats two defenders on drive for two points. Photo by Brian Cassella/Tribune" width="300" height="300" class="size-medium wp-image-1551" /></a> Evan Gilyard beats two defenders on drive for two points. Photo by Brian Cassella/Tribune[/caption]

With 22 seconds on the clock and Simeon leading 67-66, Smith dribbled quickly up the right side for the Friars and pulled up outside the arc, pump-faked, then went up for a jumpshot, crashing into Simeon sophomore Talen Horton Tucker, an NBA move that most high school and college refs won’t call - especially when it may determine the winner of the game.  But in the Fenwick gymnasium, the ref blew the whistle and gave Smith three foul shots.  There was no doubt in my mind the ultra-talented Smith, who should be considered for Illinois Mr. Basketball, would sink all three and put Fenwick up 69-67. He did.

Trying to answer, Gilyard came flying down the middle of the court, drove the lane and a foul was called.  One of Simeon’s best freethrow shooters, Gilyard sank the first one and it looked like the game was going to overtime. With Fenwick fans collective breath held, and eyeballs wide throughout the gym, Gilyard’s second freethrow missed badly to the left. As the ball came down, Fenwick pulled down the rebound and Nixon was fouled. He sank both freethrows to cap the win at 71-68 as the horn sounded and the student section emptied onto the court to congratulate their schoolmates, including Smith who finished with 38 points and Nixon with 12.  Simeon’s Norvell finished with 25, Gilyard 19 and Thomas 14. 
[caption id="attachment_1548" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/ct-photos-boys-hoops-fenwick-vs-simeon-2016011-002.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/ct-photos-boys-hoops-fenwick-vs-simeon-2016011-002-300x300.jpg" alt="Photo by Brian Cassella/Tribune" width="300" height="300" class="size-medium wp-image-1548" /></a> Photo by Brian Cassella/Tribune[/caption]

As the fans filed out of the gym with happy faces, there is no doubt that this MLK Day will be remembered by the Friar faithful for years to come. And high school basketball in Chicago continues to be a cheap ticket and really fun experience. 
