<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/Colbert-Stephen-2.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/Colbert-Stephen-2.jpg" alt="Colbert-Stephen-2" width="300" height="300" class="alignright size-full wp-image-1372" /></a>

When Stephen Colbert took over the hot seat from Mr. David Letterman on September 8 of 2015, there was no smooth, seamless transition. It was out with the old and in with the new. As a big David Letterman fan since 1978, I believe ol’ Dave was night-in and night-out the funniest, most entertaining person on television since he launched <em>Late Night</em> on NBC in 1982 and then the <em>The Late Show</em> on CBS in 1993.  But Dave’s show ran its course and the last five years felt like the true King of Late Night was just going through the motions, while all of a sudden deciding to take political positions, something he hadn’t done over the first 26 years of his show. 
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/US-Obama-Mideast-Isra_Horo-3-e1363898256893-635x357.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/US-Obama-Mideast-Isra_Horo-3-e1363898256893-635x357-300x168.jpg" alt="US-Obama-Mideast-Isra_Horo-3-e1363898256893-635x357" width="300" height="168" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1316" /></a>

If you watched, you know there were no jokes about President Barack Obama during the entire first four years of the administration. It wasn’t until the second term that jokes about the President, a staple for late-night talk shows, were inserted into the monologue. Fat jokes about Chris Christie were also flying out of Dave’s mouth, a real no-no in this day and age of awareness for the life-threatening dangers of anorexia nervosa and bulimia. The clever monologue writer, Bill Scheft, wrote those inappropriate jokes, but Dave had to approve them and read them.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/01/Madonna-photo.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/01/Madonna-photo.jpg" alt="Madonna photo" width="179" height="119" class="alignright size-full wp-image-938" /></a>
Also, over the course of his three decades on the air, Dave was often called mean by some Hollywood celebrities who didn’t like his direct questions. Cher and Madonna led that criticism, but that wasn’t the reason for the change. The real inspiration was a drop in audience from 3.1 million in the 2012-2013 season to 2.8 million the following year. When the search began for a new host, <em>The Colbert Report</em> had the largest audience among adults 18-49 (April 2013), beating out Jay Leno and <em>The Tonight Show</em> for the first time. And Colbert’s appeal to college students and young men 18-34 meant CBS could put a new host in the hot seat who would bring in a built-in audience. 

The one wild card on the show was the format and how would Colbert fair as the real Stephen Colbert. Apparently, there was quite a bit of curiosity about this as the first show drew a whopping 6.6 million viewers. Yes, Stephen is now himself on <em>The Late Show</em>, but he is bringing an entire bag of success from <em>The Colbert Report</em>, most notably the first segment at the desk. 

Once Stephen sits at the desk, his very loyal core of fans are treated to the format that worked so well on <em>The Colbert Report</em>. He will usually address a political subject or news events with the photo of that subject or event coming on the screen to his right. For his fans, this is <em>The Colbert Report</em> continued, although Stephen is not presenting it with an attitude his CR character had delivered for nine years, mimicking the persona of <em>FOX News</em> star, Bill O’Reilly, with a character voice that is low, more assertive and authoritative. He presents it as the real Stephen Colbert, but it’s the same humor, the same wit, the same bit, so the fans know their comedy hero lives on and is now playing to a much larger audience with the potential to grow even bigger on the more accessible CBS Network. 
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/colbertrump.jpg.CROP_.promovar-mediumlarge.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/colbertrump.jpg.CROP_.promovar-mediumlarge-300x166.jpg" alt="colbertrump.jpg.CROP.promovar-mediumlarge" width="300" height="166" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1521" /></a>

There have been many memorable moments during that first segment, more than a few used Donald Trump. One of my favorites right out of the gate was when Colbert said, “Right after announcing he was running for President, Donald Trump called the Mexicans racists and John McCain a coward. Given that, his campaign slogan might as well be: Trump ’16, You’re Stupid and Ugly!”

For CR fans, that’s the comedy they expect to be served. However, they get a much bigger helping of the “ha ha” because now Stephen has the opportunity to show America his full repertoire including singing, dancing, his very funny characters performing in sketches, satirical smarts, silliness, wackiness and a level of energy which is incredible to see each night. 
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/498483942.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/498483942-199x300.jpg" alt="498483942" width="199" height="300" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1530" /></a>
One of the really silly bits he did was with the very smart, but very silly John Cleese. They were the men of big hats, which were visually silly, and then traded funny statements, making the bit look like it came right out of <em>Monty Python</em>. Great stuff! (Clip below)

His fans let him know each evening that they aren’t letting go of the love they have for <em>The Colbert Report</em> as they chant “Stephen! Stephen! reminiscent of the chants heard on <em>Comedy Central</em>.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/NBNvOuz.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/NBNvOuz-300x168.jpg" alt="NBNvOuz" width="300" height="168" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1524" /></a>

Over the past three months, the show and Stephen have continued to grow as he continues to present new segments, new characters, new bits. And here’s the major point: When you tune in to <em>The Late Show</em>, you don’t really have to check to see who will be on the show. All you have to know is that Stephen Colbert is the host. He takes every segment and every guest and keeps it interesting and funny. He is very aware of the attention span of America and keeps the pace moving. When a guest sits in that chair, they aren’t receiving the softball questions: How have you been? What’s new? What have you been up to? Nope, Stephen has the questions ready and delivers them with an energy that signals to the guests that they need to keep pace. Perhaps the only guest thus far who didn’t understand that was Bruce Willis, who paused and reflected before answering the question, leaving a gap that resulted in Stephen saying, “Should I get an egg timer?”  

Burt Reynolds was also a little slow with his response, but Stephen respectfully cut him some slack, given Reynolds age. Nonetheless, both were very funny segments.

Carly Simon remarked during the questions that his fast-paced interview-style helped her, because she struggles with a stutter and the pace helped her avoid stuttering, which she appreciated. Then, he asked her to sing a duet with him for the song, <em>Mockingbird</em>, which he very nicely sang the harmonies to Simon's incredible vocals. (Clip below)

He has introduced some really funny segments. <em>Big Questions with even Bigger Stars</em> with Tom Hanks was a gem of a bit; an absolutely hilarious sketch with James Bond actor Daniel Craig trying to rent a car may be the high point of hilarity on the show up until now. There was Stephen interviewing his long-time Second City pal, Steve Carell, and then singing a wonderful melodic duet with him. In <em>Hans Wars</em>, he pretended to be auditioning for the Hans Solo part for writer/director J.J. Abrams so Harrison Ford would decide to take the part. So funny!
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/bill-maher-and-stephen-colbert-had-a-curse-filled-debate-about-donald-trump.jpg.png"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/bill-maher-and-stephen-colbert-had-a-curse-filled-debate-about-donald-trump.jpg-300x225.png" alt="bill-maher-and-stephen-colbert-had-a-curse-filled-debate-about-donald-trump.jpg" width="300" height="225" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1519" /></a>

Perhaps the best interview was with controversial HBO political talk show host, Bill Maher, who made it combative, but came out on the losing end of the verbal combat. He started it with, “I probably wouldn’t be invited to your dinner party, because we are very opposite.” Stephen was literally taken aback by the remark, shifting back in his chair and looking a bit surprised, but also realizing “it was on.” He quickly leaned back into Maher’s space and met the confrontation head on.  At one point, Colbert really made Maher look stupid after Maher misrepresented a statement made only seconds earlier as "a big lecture" by Colbert pressing him to return to the Church, as opposed to the polite invitation viewers witnessed. This was mono o mono, two big comedy giants throwing out the PC and letting the statements fly. Loved it! Great stuff! (Clip below)
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/Nussbaum-The-Late-Show-with-Stephen-Colbert-Debut-1200-630-09101757.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/Nussbaum-The-Late-Show-with-Stephen-Colbert-Debut-1200-630-09101757-300x157.jpg" alt="Nussbaum-The-Late-Show-with-Stephen-Colbert-Debut-1200-630-09101757" width="300" height="157" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1525" /></a>

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/lead_960.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/lead_960-300x224.jpg" alt="lead_960" width="300" height="224" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1523" /></a>

Personally, I have only one issue with the show. They have made a definitive decision to present off-beat musical acts. Perhaps this appeals to the younger audience they are trying to attract. I am over 50 and a lover of alternative rock, but really any good music. For the majority of the acts Stephen introduces, that's when I turn the channel. 

There is so much that can be written about the unique blend of remarkable talent, interesting interviews, political debate with the candidates, silliness with the kings of laughter, and really creative sketches presented each evening. There is most certainly a major gap between the intelligent satirical comedy Colbert presents as opposed to the silly guy-at-the-party comedy Jimmy Fallon offers each night. I watched five of his shows and that was enough for me to stay away from NBC. So my recommendation is this: If you are someone who stays up to watch late night talk shows, or records them, watch five of Colbert's shows. If you’re not hooked by then, he’s not your brand of comedy. But for me and millions across this country, he has taken the seat of a comedy legend I loved and is now presenting an entirely new style of late night talk show that is much needed and appreciated. 
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/01/dave-at-desk.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/01/dave-at-desk.jpg" alt="dave at desk" width="199" height="149" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1004" /></a>

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/la-et-ct-les-moonves-cbs-selling-stations-20141210.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2016/01/la-et-ct-les-moonves-cbs-selling-stations-20141210-300x203.jpg" alt="la-et-ct-les-moonves-cbs-selling-stations-20141210" width="300" height="203" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1531" /></a>


Good call by Les Moonves and David Letterman for hiring this Colbert fellow and making late night talk interesting and really funny again.
