Here’s the facts on why from the Social Security Administration, which reveals that 38 percent of all American workers made less than $20,000 last year, 51 percent made less than $30,000, 62 percent made less than $40,000, and 71 percent made less than $50,000.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/UnemploymentLineMichiganSnow.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/UnemploymentLineMichiganSnow-300x192.jpg" alt="Unemployment Line" width="300" height="192" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1490" /></a>
Now consider, these are the Americans who are working. The SSA reports there are 7.9 million working-age Americans who are officially unemployed. But worse, there are another 94.7 million working-age Americans considered not in the labor force.  Added together, that is 102.6 million working age Americans who are not working. 

So is it any wonder that people are angry?

Now let’s add to that the underlying distrust factor of mainstream America for the wealthy. We don’t trust the six big banks who hold the majority of the assets, 9.8 trillion, and won’t lend it out to the little guy or small businesses or mortgages for entrepreneurs. No, they have bet that money, 278 trillion in derivatives to be exact, on investments they consider beneficial for themselves. So the government bailed this group out through the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008. Since then, the six big banks have grown even wealthier, won’t lend money to the little guy, and are placing themselves in a position where they can fail and sink the economy even worse than last time.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/six-big-u-s-banks-need-to-raise-an-additional-120-billion.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/six-big-u-s-banks-need-to-raise-an-additional-120-billion-300x167.jpg" alt="six-big-u-s-banks-need-to-raise-an-additional-120-billion" width="300" height="167" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1491" /></a>

Add to that the number of the top one percent of wealthy individuals who are hiding their money in overseas accounts so they don’t have to pay taxes.  The poorest Americans have to pay taxes, while many of the richest escape.

So with a very important U.S. Presidential election coming up, offering the majority of Americans an opportunity  to vote their disapproval of all of this, what are many of them saying they will do according to the polls? In the Republican primary race, in a consensus of polls, 37.5 percent of those polled said they would vote for a billionaire businessman in the top one percent of wealth, who has been factually proven to be a consistent liar. Yes, Donald Trump.  
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/nbc-fires-donald-trump-after-he-calls-mexicans-rapists-and-drug-runners.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/nbc-fires-donald-trump-after-he-calls-mexicans-rapists-and-drug-runners-300x225.jpg" alt="nbc-fires-donald-trump-after-he-calls-mexicans-rapists-and-drug-runners" width="300" height="225" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1477" /></a>

The Donald’s daily fibs have earned him more four-Pinocchio ratings (highest fib rating) for his "whoppers" by the The Washington Post Fact Checker team than any other candidate. 

So if you consider yourself a fairly bright American and are fed up with the top one percent keeping and growing their wealth while you suffer economically, then the election is the place to direct your anger and vote.  

If you have watched all of the debates and read the news accounts to educate yourself about the candidates, you should be aware that on the GOP side, the most logical, rationale and smartest candidates to choose from include: Rick Santorum, John Kasich and George Pataki. Personally, I hope I have the opportunity to vote for one of them, however not one of them is doing well in the polls, which is astounding to say the least. But each would be better than Trump; significantly better than Trump!
