/12/SpotlightTIFF2015-300x112.jpg" alt="SpotlightTIFF2015" width="300" height="112" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1443" /></a>

I am a practicing Catholic and have read the great religion reporter Jason Berry’s books, so I was well aware of the details behind the scandal. This movie focuses on a team of dedicated Boston Globe reporters working against the grain of a Catholic-dominated society, many of whom preferred to look the other way and practice their faith in denial of the evil that was taking place in many of the parishes throughout Boston. I will never understand that mentality and that choice since Jesus stood for truth. Christianity is truth, not a cover-up of evil acts, whether it be pedophiles taking advantage of the priesthood or misdeeds in the Roman Curia or Vatican Bank. Thank goodness we now have Pope Francis leading the Church and working hard to clean up those problems.
[caption id="attachment_1435" align="alignleft" width="261"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/Law-photo.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/Law-photo.jpg" alt="Cardinal Bernard Law" width="261" height="193" class="size-full wp-image-1435" /></a> Cardinal Bernard Law[/caption]

I am also a journalist and <em>All the President’s Men</em> is a movie that inspired me toward the newspaper business following college. Like that famous 1976 movie about the Washington Post’s great investigative reporting duo, Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein, <em>Spotlight</em> presents the story of the investigative team at the Boston Globe pursuing the pedophile priest scandal taking place throughout the Archdiocese of Boston. This was all being directed by the very powerful Cardinal Bernard Law with the transfer of criminal priests from one parish to the next, destroying the lives of more than a thousand young boys and their families. 
[caption id="attachment_1444" align="alignright" width="222"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/jason-berry-pic.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/jason-berry-pic.jpg" alt="Journalist Jason Berry" width="222" height="224" class="size-full wp-image-1444" /></a> Journalist Jason Berry[/caption]

When this movie came out, Jason Berry wrote that he had known Father Law when the young priest was a civil rights activist in Mississippi and editor of the Mississippi Register, where he received death threats for his strong positions on civil rights. At that time, Berry found Law to be a very intelligent and conscientious young priest who stood up for the civil rights of African Americans. Law seemed to be a man of integrity, but somewhere along the line, the conscientious objector’s conscience stopped objecting.  In Berry’s PBS Frontline documentary, he addressed “institutionalism” as one of the key reasons many priests, bishops and cardinals went along with this sick and twisted system of crime against youth.  In other words, they were “company men” going along with the organization as opposed to the much larger and more important responsibility of representing Christ. 

In his book, <em>Render Unto Rome</em>, Berry wrote about an important 1989 decision that led to the continuance of abuse and ultimately the revelation and scale of the scandal. From <em>Render Unto Rome</em>:

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/render-unto-rome.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/render-unto-rome-196x300.jpg" alt="render unto rome" width="196" height="300" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1445" /></a>“The American bishops had been stymied in their early efforts to confront the crisis. In 1989 the U.S. bishops had canonists seek permission from the Vatican to defrock priests proven to be severe abusers. That authority lay with the pope. And John Paul said no.” (Page 79)
“In April 2000 bishops from the English-speaking world met with Vatican officials, pleading for help. In 2001 John Paul signed a document that (Cardinal Joseph) Ratzinger all but drafted, which consolidated the responsibility on the explosive issue in his office.” (Page 80) 

Cardinal Ratzinger, later Pope Benedict, was in charge of managing this issue as the prefect for the Congregation for the Doctrine of Faith (CDF). Up until 2001, most of the investigations conducted by that office involved theologians who had strayed from the orthodoxy. But from 2001-2010, the CDF dealt with more than 3,000 cases of priests accused of abusing children.

[caption id="attachment_1439" align="alignright" width="290"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/Ratzinger-photo.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/Ratzinger-photo.jpg" alt="Pope Benedict and Cardinal Law" width="290" height="174" class="size-full wp-image-1439" /></a> Pope Benedict and Cardinal Law[/caption]
The movie doesn’t cover that aspect of the scandal but for the sake of the story, focuses on Boston, because it was an investigation that became very personal for many of the reporters on the Spotlight staff.  All had grown up in Boston and were raised Catholics. Many were lapsed or now practicing a different faith.  The Spotlight editor Walter “Robby” Robinson, played by Michael Keaton, had attended Boston College High School and had to confront former schoolmates and friends who were either in denial over the illicit activities taking place, or just preferred to turn a blind eye to all of it. Even when they found out one of their classmates had been abused, some were willing to dismiss it. It was also very personal for Spotlight reporter Sacha Pfeiffer, played by Rachel McAdams, who went to mass each week with her Nana, a devout Catholic. When the scandal stories were published, the movie showed her Nana crying. I’m sure that reflected what thousands of Catholics in Boston experienced during those sad days.

[caption id="attachment_1437" align="alignleft" width="300"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/Michael-Keaton.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/Michael-Keaton-300x160.jpg" alt="Michael Keaton and Rachel McAdams" width="300" height="160" class="size-medium wp-image-1437" /></a> Michael Keaton and Rachel McAdams[/caption]

The personal side of this story is the side that many Catholics can relate, because there is nothing more personal than an individual’s religion. So what would any Catholic have done if placed in the same circumstance? To me, that’s the question each should walk out of the theater considering. Who would do the right thing? Who would turn a blind eye and go along with the program? 

Research has shown the majority of the priests are very good and dedicated men who help the Catholics in their pews understand and practice their faith. Even with one good priest though, Catholics should walk into their church with eyes open. It’s very difficult to identify a pedophile who has infiltrated the now accountable system. From reading about the scandal, along with other news stories about what takes place in schools and youth organizations, it’s obvious that pedophiles target opportunities where they are placed in a position of authority and have access to boys.  Therefore, at some point the Catholic Church became a breeding ground for these gay pedophiles. The movie makes it clear that these evil men sought out boys who were from poor families and had just suffered the loss of a father. They were taking advantage of an authoritative position with these boys who were hurting emotionally. They also sought out gay boys who were hurting and vulnerable.

[caption id="attachment_1465" align="alignright" width="300"]<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/Francis-with-curia.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/Francis-with-curia-300x194.jpg" alt="Pope Francis addressing Curia" width="300" height="194" class="size-medium wp-image-1465" /></a> Pope Francis addressing Curia[/caption]

As Pope Francis has stated many times, don’t dismiss the evil of the devil. It’s everywhere. Thankfully, the reporting team at the Globe had the courage to identify the evil in Boston and follow through on the investigation, printing the stories that ignited other investigations throughout America and the world. During the time of the scandal, the movie quotes a researcher who states that at that time, six percent of priests in an Archdiocese were pedophiles.  That proved true in Boston. Now, with the efforts by the Catholic Church to be transparent, certainly since Jorge Mario Bergoglio became Pope in March of 2013, the hope is that percentage is far less as he works to clean house. 

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/catholic-praying.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/catholic-praying.jpg" alt="catholic praying" width="300" height="168" class="alignright size-full wp-image-1446" /></a>

Despite the scandal and all of the negative media produced to cover it, it’s always important to remember that being Catholic is about practicing the faith. If and when the organization fails, which it has done many times over its 2000-year history, it only means that some of the shepherds responsible for leading the Church have not lived up to their responsibility to God. But the Catholic faith is - and always will be - as pure as it was when Jesus first gave us the <em>good news</em>. If a situation arises at a parish where a Catholic is no longer comfortable practicing the only faith given to us by Jesus Christ, then find another parish where there is a comfort and confidence level. I have been to parishes all over the country and I know for certain there are far more good priests now than at any other time in my lifetime. I’m always amazed to walk into a new Catholic church and be completely inspired by the educated and passionate words of a dedicated priest.

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/jesus.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/12/jesus.jpg" alt="jesus" width="194" height="260" class="alignright size-full wp-image-1447" /></a>

So when it comes to joining a parish, Catholics need to do their research and be selective. The church selected shouldn’t be the closest one to home, but the parish with a priest who each parishioner can decide if they like and respect.
   
The scandal was a very difficult and challenging time for Catholics. But we should never give up on our faith. Keep the faith and pray for the Catholic Church. 
<a href="http://https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UVb_n5QsykY">Invitation to Sunday Mass</a>
