<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/11/turkey_1491551c.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/11/turkey_1491551c-300x187.jpg" alt="turkey_1491551c" width="300" height="187" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1422" /></a>
	
So what are they warning us about?  WHO? The researchers. According to their review, processed meat, which means it has been cured, salted or smoked, is carcinogenic. That means it has the potential to cause cancer. Those meats include bacon, sausages, hot dogs, salami, corned beef, beef jerky as well as canned meat and meat-based sauces.  Red meat, which they term as “probably carcinogenic” includes beef, lamb and pork. 


Says WHO? That’s right.

What? Second base.

Is this ground-breaking news? I don’t know. Third base. Yes, doctors have known for years about the dietary risk-factors associated with meat. I guess they just felt like they needed to remind us of this right before the holidays. WHO? That’s right. 

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/11/Abbott-and-Costello-2.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/11/Abbott-and-Costello-2-225x300.jpg" alt="Abbott and Costello 2" width="225" height="300" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1420" /></a>

I read another story in the Tribune where the report stated 50 grams of bacon increases the risk of cancer by 18 percent. What? Second base. But the reporter made it clear that you would have to eat 50 grams of bacon each day to increase that risk.  And let’s not forget, other researchers have revealed that meat provides valuable nutrients. Says WHO? No, some other guys. 

Bacon is absolutely a favorite of millions of Americans. WHO? Again, not them.
 
Personally, I eat bacon about once a month, so I’m not going to change that habit. 

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/11/bacon.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/11/bacon.jpg" alt="bacon" width="253" height="199" class="alignright size-full wp-image-1423" /></a>

So in light of the timing of this news, before the holidays, I wonder how many Americans will change their holiday eating habits. I don’t know. Third base. 

Me? Nope, I’m not changing a thing. Last year, I found out about the Holiday Gift Check Program and ordered gift checks for my clients so they could go out and buy a turkey for the holidays. I got great feedback from each of them, which I appreciated. This year, I got a notice that the program is adding ham, so if clients want to purchase a ham instead of a turkey, they can do so. Like bacon, if you eat turkey or ham on the holidays as a treat, that’s not going to cause cancer. If you ate it every day, then yes, you would be taking a risk. Says WHO? That’s right. 

<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/11/Ham.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/11/Ham-300x251.jpg" alt="108006 P.140-141+" width="300" height="251" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1421" /></a>

But I say, eat processed meat on occasion and red meat in moderation and you won’t have a problem. Says WHO? No, says me.  Now I’ve got to go order my checks so my clients can partake in turkey and/or ham over the holidays. If you are interested in doing the same, or giving them to employees or friends, you can go to www.giftcheckprogram.com.

Happy Holidays to the meat-eaters of America! WHO? No, everyone else.

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iFemw_6a-Tg">He don't eat no meat</a>

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kTcRRaXV-fg">Abbott and Costello</a>

