<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/Colbert-Stephen-2.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/Colbert-Stephen-2.jpg" alt="Colbert-Stephen-2" width="300" height="300" class="alignright size-full wp-image-1372" /></a>

Now, CBS has shown great wisdom in selecting Mr. Colbert to replace the great David Letterman as host of <em>The Late Show</em>. The book was updated last year due to all the changes in the industry, which is reflected in this chapter. The names of celebrities and shows have been altered slightly just to underscore this is satire, however most of it is true with background facts. Here is the chapter. Hope you enjoy it. 

<ul><strong>A TALE OF TWO TALK SHOWS</strong></ul>
It was late on a Friday evening in January of 2010 when two good friends from the popular cable channel ComedyCenter entered their new favorite Italian bistro after finishing the taping of their final show of the week.

Stephen Clobear and Soupy Stewart, two incredibly funny, talented and smart political comedy stars had started a tradition of going out after the final show of the week. Stewart, whose real name is Leftonritz, but had it legally changed because he was tired of all the cracker jokes, can be described as a survivor -- a great entertainment success story.

He grew up in New Jersey and first tried Standup comedy in 1986 under the name Shecky Tuna, bombed, got the nerve to try it again under the name Soupy Stewart and within a few years was soon receiving opportunities to perform on ComedyCenter and Fun TV. In 1993, he was one of the frontrunners for the host of the popular late night talk show, Good Night, after Daniel Littleton bolted to do The Big Show on another network. Instead of Stewart, the executive producer at Good Night selected a writer and producer for Saturday Evening Theater, Conan O’Ryan, to host the national talk show.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/john-stewart.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/john-stewart-239x300.jpg" alt="Jon Stewart Portrait Session" width="239" height="300" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1375" /></a>

But the 5’10”, good-looking, energetic and determined neighborhood tiddlywinks champion from New Jersey forged on, and after a few other failed TV gigs, was given the chance to take over the Craig Show on ComedyCenter when that legendary comedy giant, Craig Kiljoy, left for a late night network show.

ComedyCenter renamed the show The Soupy Stewart Show and the comedian soon learned that sometimes it takes more than just a break to achieve success. Sometimes it takes the right break. Stewart was a hit and went on to become one of the most popular television personalities in America, winning Emmy, Peabody, and Grammy awards, not to mention the opportunity to host two Academy Awards shows, perhaps the highest honor given to anyone in his business.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/838-495_StephenColbert.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/838-495_StephenColbert-251x300.jpg" alt="838-495_StephenColbert" width="251" height="300" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1368" /></a>

His buddy, Stephen Clobear, has somewhat of a similar story, searching for the right break. He grew up in South Carolina, but went to Northwestern University to study theater and ended up at the famed Compass City Theater where he developed his talent. Later, he took off for New York with a couple of other Compass City comedy actors, where they tried their sketch comedy here and there, and struggled. But in the mid-1990s, Clobear started catching a few breaks, hired as a writer for Saturday Evening Theater, often referred to as SET, then the short-lived Dana Harvey Show and finally The Soupy Stewart Show.

Working with Soupy, Clobear developed his on-air right wing republican character, a tongue-in-cheek swipe at Rush Limbaugh and Bill O’Reilly, and his star rose quickly. He became so popular, ComedyCenter spun off his character into a new show he would host called, The Clobear Report, which has become a highly successful, and often quoted show on real national news shows.

On this Friday evening, the two tired national comedy stars made their way to Guido’s Place, a restaurant Stewart happened into about a month earlier after he had taken a wrong turn into a not so nice section of Hell’s Kitchen off 8th Avenue. That evening, the owner, one Guido Manilucci, offered him dinner on the house and asked for a photo he could hang up in the center of the Wall of Fame, the most prominent place.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/mediumhellskitchenvincent-des-jardins.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/mediumhellskitchenvincent-des-jardins-300x200.jpg" alt="mediumhellskitchen(vincent des jardins)" width="300" height="200" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1374" /></a>

This pleasant and affordable experience led Stewart to start frequenting the dining establishment, despite the neighborhood, decorum, food and so on. Free food and his photo on the wall, why not? A few weeks later, he decided to make it the Friday dinner spot for him and his pal from South Carolina.

Guido, a lifelong New Yorker, spotted the two cable talk show giants entering the front door and quickly walked up to greet them.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/87514673df7b4ebc.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/87514673df7b4ebc-300x199.jpg" alt="-87514673df7b4ebc" width="300" height="199" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1370" /></a>

“Stephen and Soupy, hey how’s it going, eh?” said the middle-aged, overweight, mustached and jovial owner with a heavy New York accent. “Ya know I got your favorite table open.”

“Hey thanks Guido,” said Stewart, smiling, but looking tired from a tough week of being funny and smart, not easy in any business, but really difficult when a million people are watching you attempt it each night. “I am starved!”

“Me too!” said Clobear, following Stewart and Guido to the back of the restaurant and a small table with two rickety old chairs in a corner with red brick walls on each side, decorated only by a few lit candles, some of which were duct taped to stay in place. “Why don’t you have the chef start cookin’ up our favorites?”

“Yes,” added Stewart. “And I know Stephen and I would like a glass of your finest grape, as always, Guido my good man.”

“Hey dat sounds good Soupy,” said Guido, shrugging his shoulders, and then tilting his head from side to side, the nervous mannerisms he exhibits every time he addresses someone. “I will get on it right away. Youz twos guys go ahead and sit down, I’ll have dat bottle of chardonnay out here before you can tuck your napkin in, you know? Hey you know what I mean? Before you can tuck your napkin in. Know what I’m saying?”

“We got you gumba,” laughed Stewart whose fairly large nicely framed photo hung on the wall opposite his table. Guido was always eager to let guests know this was Soupy Stewart’s favorite hangout and THE table where he ate his meals. He never saw Soupy’s show, not once, but a young bartender, Billy O’Donnell, filled him in the show and its famous host.

“Soupy when are they going to put my photo up there?” asked Clobear, looking at the Wall of Fame where Stewart’s photo took the most prominent position at the center, surrounded by several other photos of local news celebrities in town. On the right of his signed ComedyCenter mugshot was a framed Polaroid photo of Mike Smithson, an associate producer for the 5 a.m. news at WMBC-TV. To the left was a coffee-stained photo of Mary O’Neil, the receptionist at WOOR-TV. And right below was a police lineup profile photo of the always recognized, Marty Forkin, the security guard at FLUX News for about five weeks in the late 1990s. Yes, this was a group Stewart was proud to be among, no question about it.

Clobear struggled with the thinking behind the pecking order at the restaurant.

“I gave them a signed photo a few weeks ago,” said The Clobear Report’s star, not accustomed to being snubbed by anyone, especially the owner of a rat-infested restaurant.

“The photo is up Stephen,” informed his pal. “I saw it. A beautiful spot, right over the urinal.”

“Hah, hah, you are a funny man Soupy,” chuckled Clobear, organizing the salt and pepper shakers on the table so they were lined up correctly with the napkin holder.

“I’m not kidding,” he said with a straight face. “They have no idea who you are.”

“What?”

“They had no idea who I was either until they hired a college kid to tend bar, who told them about me and the show. Unfortunately, Billy O’Donnell only lasted two days, because he couldn’t converse with Guido and his staff about network TV shows like COPS, Judge Judy and Wheel of Fortune. He never watched them. Too bad you weren’t with me the first day I came here. Your picture would be right up there with mine for all of the half-wits, nitwits and dimwits that come in this place to admire. Isn’t that what it’s all about?”

Clobear rolled his eyes, adjusted his glasses and took a sip of the water when he couldn’t help but notice the waiter serving the food at a table in front of them. “Oh my God, it’s him!”

Stewart looked over to see a dark-haired, overweight, 40-something waiter with a sagging and red-splotched apron around his waist serving the plates of pasta to an odd looking couple a few tables away -- an old businessman with a young woman that didn’t seem to be his daughter.

“Do you think they know?” asked Stewart.

“No way,” said Clobear, watching the waiter walk away from the couple’s table, back toward the kitchen area. He stopped at a station that had stacked 8-ounce glasses and large plastic pitchers of water. “Here it comes.”

“Wouldn’t’ be any fun coming here, if he didn’t” said Stewart, who watched the waiter take a pitcher, pour a glass of water, then stand up straight drinking the glass of water in his left hand, while he used his right hand to violently adjust his personal equipment, then readjust it, then went deep sea diving into his pants to make sure his moray eel was properly cared for.<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/20071204-037.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/20071204-037-300x238.jpg" alt="20071204-037" width="300" height="238" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1369" /></a>

Stewart and Clobear couldn’t help laughing at this incredibly disgusting ritual which they had watched many times, but never had the heart to tell any of the other customers prior to being served.

“Oh that’s new!” said Clobear, seeing the waiter do a two-thumbed scratch of the lower groin, finishing with a satisfied and audible, “Ahhh!”

“He should, write a book about best ways to scratch and adjust, don’t you think Stephen?” asked Stewart. “I’d book ‘em.”

Guido returned to the table and showed the two political comedy news stars a bottle of chardonnay. “Hey, dis is some of our best stuff right here guys. Youz guys are gonna luv dis!”

Clobear looked at the label as Guido turned the twist cap off of the wine bottle, “Ah yes,” he said. “2008 was a very good year! Last year, wasn’t it?”

“I’m tellin’ ya, you will luv dis!” said Guido. “Troot is, I donno ‘xactly where it comes from, but I know our guys get it off da back of a truck in da Bronx.”

“May I sniff the twistoff cap?” asked Stewart, sharing his sarcastic humor with his comedy pal, knowing it would sail right over Guido’s balding head. Clobear just put his head down and laughed, but stopped abruptly as a disturbing thought occurred to him.

“Hey Guido, I know you are aware of this, but just so there are no mixups,” said the ultra neat and clean Clobear with a look of concern on his face. “We always like you to serve our food, right? I mean you know that, don’t you?”

“I take great pride in serving youz two guys,” said Guido.

“We appreciate that,” Stewart smiled. “We just wouldn’t want that other waiter over there serving us, if it’s okay with you?”

Guido looked back over his shoulder to see the waiter Stewart was referring, now talking with a younger waiter at the water station.

“Do you mean Joey over there?” he asked, pointing toward the two men.

“Well I don’t know his name,” said Stewart, then seeing the waiter now demonstrating the two-hand grab and tug adjustment. “There, him! Tommy Tug-a-lot over there.”

Chuckling, Clobear couldn’t help but assist, “Yes, he means Sammy Scrotum Shiner there.”

Stewart wouldn’t be one-upped, “Tug McBall Scratcher.”

“Thumbs McCrank Yanker,” laughed Clobear.

“We’re like a couple of fifth graders, aren’t we Stephen?” Stewart said to his amused pal.

“We are, but we’re funny fifth graders and we get paid millions of dollars,” said the dark-haired king of dry, straight-faced humor. “Who would have thought our little wise-guy antics in grade school would take us so far, eh?”

Guido looked over at his two waiters and figured out to whom they were referring. “Hey Bobby,” he yelled across the room. “Would you mind getting your damn hands outta your pants! This is a restaurant. People eat dat food ya serve.”<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/jon.stewart.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/09/jon.stewart-300x168.jpg" alt="Jon Stewart Portrait Session" width="300" height="168" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1376" /></a>

The odd looking couple that had just been served stopped mid-chew to look up at the waiter, saw him finishing an intense game of pocket pool, put their forks down, spit the food into their napkins and called for the check.

“Scuse me gents,” said Guido, who went over to the table to talk to his now-sickened customers.

Clobear took a sip of the wine and remarked, “This is good, if you like turpentine.”

“Oh, I love turpentine,” quipped the graying Soupy Stewart Show host, looking around to make sure no-one could hear him, then spoke in a low tone of voice. “Hey Stephen, let me ask you a pretty sensitive question, if you don’t mind?”

Clobear realizing the funny had left the room for a moment and it was time for a serious conversation said, “Sure, what’s up?”

“Well, this must stay between you and me, right?”

Guido turned from the odd couples’ table and said to Stewart, “Don’t you mean to say, you and I? Ya know?”

“Wow that’s the worst case of elephant ears I’ve ever witnessed,” said a concerned looking Stewart, who lowered his head and voice even further.

“Look, no problem Soupy, go ahead,” Clobear responded, confident he would keep any secret for the man who gave him his big break in the entertainment business.

“Well, we are both really funny, right?” Stewart began.

“Right,” agreed Clobear.

“I mean, critics, viewers, everyone seems to think our shows are incredibly funny, right? That’s the same input you get, isn’t it? It’s what we have heard for several years. It’s why I get asked to host the Academy Awards and so on, right?”

“Yes, absolutely,” Clobear agreed once more, now wondering where Soupy was going with this line of questioning.

“Well, wouldn’t you think one of the networks would have made one of us, or both of us, an offer by now to take our shows to a larger audience?” asked a bewildered-looking Stewart. “I mean let’s be honest. Some of the network guys aren’t really that funny and they seem to be getting a real shot at the big-time. I love ComedyCenter and the opportunity they have given us, but it has somewhat of a limited reach, wouldn’t you agree?”

Clobear sat and considered this logic for a moment, then said, “Soupy, honestly, I think our shows are too irreverent, too controversial for the average network viewer. I don’t think you can be as politically disruptive as we are when you are on one of the three major networks. You can’t forget Soupy, our humor and views appeal to a certain audience -- college students, college graduates now in the business world who are sharp, smart people. They read the news, know what’s going on. They get it. A lot of the folks in the rural areas, and even the cities -- as we both witnessed tonight -- don’t get cable or satellite TV and depend on the networks for their programs. Do you really think a lot of those folks would like our humor? Heck no! They would hate us!”

Stewart knew his pal was right, but struggled with the idea that lesser talented comedians were getting those more prominent network slots in front of them. Not to mention the big money!

Clobear continued, “The networks need someone who can appeal to that general audience. Safer humor that will entertain without offending, keeping the ratings.”

“Even if they aren’t that funny?” asked Stewart.

“Like who?” wondered Clobear, who certainly had his own list on the subject.

“Well, I don’t want to name any names, but…” Stewart stopped when he saw the young waiter and Lance McItchy walk past them carrying a very large golden frame toward the Wall of Fame. The two waiters placed the framed photo on the floor, leaning it against the wall, while they took down the four big local celebs, including Stewart, to make room. Then they hung the new photo.

“Hey excuse me, Tug McBall Scratcher, what are you doing?” asked Stewart, who was in no mood to see his photo removed from the wall of the Condessa Del Firetrap.

“Owner said we needs to put dis new one up,” said the walking restaurant code-violation. And there, taking Stewart’s place on the wall, was an all-too-familiar face. A man they both called a friend, Conan O’Ryan.

“Well, that’s nice,” said Stewart with more than a hint of sarcasm in his voice. “First he gets to host Good Night, then The Night Show and now my spot on a wall in a restaurant that no respectable celebrity would venture into.”

“He is our friend,” reminded Clobear. “We should just be happy for him.”

“Yes, I know,” said Soupy, grimacing as Guido returned to the table. “I’m just ecstatic!”
