If you have watched his antics over these last two Presidential primaries, it's pretty difficult to take him seriously. However, Mr. Trump's statements two days ago in an interview with Bill O'Reilly, followed by his speech in Iowa yesterday, changed that circus-act perception for me.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Trump-on-Oreilly.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Trump-on-Oreilly.jpg" alt="Trump on O&#039;reilly" width="215" height="121" class="alignright size-full wp-image-1347" /></a>

In the O'Reilly interview and then the Iowa speech, Donald Trump hit several hot button issues for many Americans and told the country how he will fix their problems.

Here are the issues he addressed:
1. "China has taken our jobs, our manufacturing but we owe them trillions. How does that work? Is that magic act? For companies that want to keep sending their jobs overseas to China or down to Mexico, I'll send my top negotiators in, and believe me, these guys are sharks - tough guys - and believe me they will get a deal done that will bring the jobs back to America and make this country great again."
2. "I am going to have gangs out of here faster than you can turn your head."
3.  "When I am elected President, Ford and Nabisco won't be building factories in Mexico, because I would set a 35% rate on everything they try to sell back to America. They'll be building their car manufacturing plants here and keeping them here."
4. "We send our kids to college and they build up a massive debt. Then after they graduate, they can't find jobs because they have been shipped overseas. I'll end that and bring the jobs back to America."
5. "I am going to build a really high wall across the border so no-one from Mexico can illegally come into our country. The Chinese built the Great Wall of China and that worked pretty well for them. I'm going to do even better."
6. "I don't take money from lobbyists. I was offered five million from a guy, a really nice guy, I know him, and I turned him down. Am I stupid? I don't think so. I'm just not going to have him walk into my office two years after I'm President and tell me what I have to do. Meanwhile, the other candidates are taking that money and guess what? When Ford says I want to keep the factory in Mexico, they'll say okay because the lobbyist already helped fund their campaigns." <a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Hillary.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Hillary.jpg" alt="Hillary" width="261" height="193" class="alignright size-full wp-image-1348" /></a>

A few weeks ago, I wrote that Donald Trump would only last six months. Based on what he has done this week, I would have to say that my speculation is dead wrong. Those messages have great appeal for a lot of Americans who are fed up with bought-and-paid-for politicians. Hillary Clinton is the epitome of the prototypical politician and every time Donald Trump gives a talk like he did in Iowa, she looks worse to anyone who is an independent or conservative. Left-wing liberals will continue to support her, even though she is standing behind Planned Parenthood and their horrific actions and attitude selling parts of aborted babies. 
 
In 1992, Ross Perot - another millionaire - ran for President and like Trump, told it like he saw it. He was a bit more of a politician than Trump, but perhaps it was Perot's GOP run that really paved the way for The Donald. More likely, it's millions of Americans who are hurting right now, losing their jobs and watching their kids come out of college with little hope for landing a job. Longtime U.S. Senator, Bill Bradley, a man of great integrity, has said that today, U.S. Senators and Representatives in Congress spend about four days of their week out seeking campaign contributions. Seeking large campaign contributions is pretty much a fulltime time job for everyone other than Trump, who is running for President. They are accepting large campaign contributions to give themselves a chance to win the White House. So all of the Congress people, all of those candidates for President who are taking the contributions, common sense tells you there will be a price tag attached by the contributors. As Trump says, those contributors are going to come knocking when they need something done. He says he knows, because he used to be the king of contributors. He knows how it works.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Megyn-Kelly.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Megyn-Kelly-300x200.jpg" alt="Megyn Kelly" width="300" height="200" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1309" /></a>
Now here's the other point. Donald Trump started his day off yesterday, taking a shot on Twitter at popular FOX News anchor Megyn Kelly, who asked him a few tough questions during the debate, which he was offended by. Then he holds a press conference and has a well-known Latino anchorman form Univision escorted out of the press conference because he was trying to get Trump to answer his statements regarding deporting Hispanics. The fact that none of this is hurting Trump in the polls tells us that many Americans don't have problem with any of those actions. It tells us many Americans are rightfully more concerned about bringing jobs back to America, than Donald Trump's behavior with the news media. And if it takes a rude, crude, obnoxious, self-centered President to do it, they have his vote. 
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/TimeToGetTough_Cover.grid-4x2.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/TimeToGetTough_Cover.grid-4x2-198x300.jpg" alt="TimeToGetTough_Cover.grid-4x2" width="198" height="300" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1352" /></a>

The normal rules of politics are out the window here. The question is, are there enough Americans who believe Donald Trump can do what he says he will do if he is elected President. I no longer believe that he can't win. If his support in the polls continues to grow, which based on this week I believe it will, it may be Trump versus Hillary for the nomination. 

