" width="300" height="225" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1277" /></a>

Over the course of the past two years, Pope Francis has been working to transition the Church as a perfect reflection of Jesus Christ, ridding the 2000 year-old institution of entrenched hypocritical habits, questionable business practices, criminal actions and cover-ups. It has been Pope Francis’ efforts to “clean house” that have Catholics, lapsed-Catholics and non-Catholics paying attention to the Pope and the Catholic Church with a new optimism. Pope Francis has a big job ahead of him and it will take time, but it’s encouraging for all to see his determination. Like so many, I am very grateful to have a Pope like Francis in my lifetime.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Vatican-City.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Vatican-City-300x239.jpg" alt="Vatican City" width="300" height="239" class="alignleft size-medium wp-image-1279" /></a>

Since moving back to Chicago five years ago, I have learned that despite the negative image the Catholic Church gained since news of the scandal broke in 2002, this city continues to be filled with practicing Catholics, committed to the faith.  I have been a parishioner of several Catholic churches in my lifetime - in Chicago, Kalamazoo and Atlanta - and have attended mass at churches across the country and overseas. So when moving to the southwest suburbs in 2010, we searched for a church and found St. Jude in New Lenox, a special church to be sure.  I feel very lucky to have found St. Jude where my family and I have the opportunity to listen to the best priest I have ever heard speak at mass. Father Bill Sullivan’s positive and encouraging demeanor, combined with his great knowledge of the Bible and ability to educate parishioners by providing the history and context of each reading and Gospel story, helps lift some of the mystery of our faith. He is such a great gift to all in the parish, carrying on the true Apostolic tradition and inspiring his flock.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Father-Bill.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Father-Bill-200x300.jpg" alt="Father Bill" width="200" height="300" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1278" /></a>

Although Father Bill is now in his 70s and battling health issues, he remains positive and upbeat, always smiling.  I look forward to attending masses celebrated by him, knowing I will learn something new about the Gospel, Old Testament readings, Jesus, the Apostles or early Jewish customs. He always seems to provide some insight that has impact and re-energizes my faith, as if he just threw a pair of jumper cables on me and revved up God’s engine of hope, faith and love. I appreciate it because I know it helps me become a better Catholic, a better Christian, a better person. 

The parishioners of St. Jude love this Augustinian priest.  I see so many people approach Father Bill in the Narthex of St. Jude after mass, whether he is the celebrant of the mass or not. They want to say hello to him, hug him, let him know they appreciate seeing him. Why? It’s simple. They see Jesus in him and he makes them feel good. He cares about them. He tries to help them.  In this day and age when priests are so busy, with such demanding schedules, for Father Bill to be so upbeat and helpful all the time, is absolutely amazing! 
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Tom-1.jpg"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Tom-1.jpg" alt="Tom 1" width="209" height="241" class="alignleft size-full wp-image-1280" /></a>

One of the other aspects of St. Jude that makes it a very special church is the musical director, Tom Labanauskus, a highly talented musician and singer whose vocals pierce straight through to the soul, filling the church with the most beautiful melodies carrying words of spiritual inspiration.  Tom performs at most of the masses, but also directs the church choir, which is absolutely heaven-sent.
<a href="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Tom-2.png"><img src="http://www.chicagonow.com/newsboy/files/2015/08/Tom-2-300x199.png" alt="Tom 2" width="300" height="199" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-1281" /></a>

To share the experience of attending St. Jude, I knew words wouldn’t suffice, so I created this video. Hopefully for those Catholics who have left the Church or non-Catholics who have been considering joining, this will help them take that first step into the pews.
